<section xml:id="section-week6-activity">
  <title>Week 6 Activity</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-matrix-action">
    <title>Matrix Action</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In <xref ref="subsection-matrix-types-in-r2" />, I gave
          the matrices for rotations by
          <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m> radians, <m>\pi</m> radians, and
          <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m> radians. I also defined reflections over the
          <m>x</m>-axis, <m>y</m>-axs, the line <m>y=x</m>, and the
          line <m>y=-x</m>. For all seven of these transformations,
          check that the matrix action acts as expected on the vectors
          <m> \left( \begin{matrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{matrix} \right)</m>,
          <m> \left( \begin{matrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{matrix} \right)</m>,
          <m> \left( \begin{matrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{matrix} \right)</m>
          and <m> \left( \begin{matrix} 1 \\ -1 \end{matrix}
          \right)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I have seven matrices, each of which acts on the four given
          vectors. I'll go through the actions one by one, starting
          with rotation by <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 + 0 \\ 1 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 - 1 \\ 0 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 - 1 \\ 1 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ - 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 + 1 \\ 1  + 0
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          All four vectors are indeed sent to their rotations by a
          quarter turn. Now look at the rotation by <m>\pi</m>.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 + 0 \\ 0 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 + 0 \\ 0 - 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \\ -1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 + 0 \\ 0 + -1 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \\ -1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ - 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 + 0 \\ 0 + 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          All of these vectors are indeed rotated by half a turn.
          (Notice that this is the same as <q>reflection</q> about the
          origin: each vector is sent to its negative. Now look at the
          rotation by <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 0  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 + 0 \\ -1 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \\ -1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 0  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 + 1 \\ 0 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 0  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 + 1 \\ -1 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ -1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 0  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ - 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 - 1 \\ -1 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \\ -1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          All of these vectors are sent to their rotation by three
          quarters of a turn. Notice that I  could also interpret this a
          rotation by a quarter turn clockwise. Now look at reflection
          over the <m>x</m>-axis. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 + 0 \\ 0 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 + 0 \\ 0 - 1 \\
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \\ -1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 + 0 \\ 0 + -1 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ -1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ - 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 + 0 \\ 0 + 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The sign of the <m>y</m> coordinate of each vector is
          changed, which is exactly what I expect for reflection over
          the <m>x</m>-axis. Now look at reflection over the
          <m>y</m>-axis. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 + 0 \\ 0 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 + 0 \\ 0 + 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 + 0 \\ 0 + 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ - 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 + 0 \\ 0 - 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \\ -1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The <m>x</m> coordinate has now changed in sign, which is as
          expected. Now look at the reflection over the line
          <m>y=x</m>.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 + 0 \\ 1 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 + 1 \\ 0 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 + 1 \\ 1 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ - 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 - 1 \\ 1 + 0
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The two coordinates are exchanged, which is exactly what I
          would expect for this reflection. Finally, look at the
          reflection over the line <m>y=-x</m>. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp -1 \\ -1 \amp 0  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 + 0 \\ -1 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \\ -1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp -1 \\ -1 \amp 0  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 - 1 \\ 0 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \\ 0
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp -1 \\ -1 \amp 0  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 - 1 \\ -1 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                -1 \\ -1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 \amp -1 \\ -1 \amp 0  
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ - 1
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                0 + 1 \\ -1 + 0 
              \end{matrix} \right) = 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \\ -1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The coordinates are switched and the signs are changed,
          which is what I would expect with this reflection.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate this matrix action.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              -5 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
              4 \amp -5 \amp -7 \amp 1 \\
              1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -8 \\
            \end{matrix} \right) 
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              4 \\ -1 \\ -1 \\ -1 
            \end{matrix} \right)
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I apply the matrix action algorithm: going along the rows
          of the matrix and down the column vector, multiplying paired
          terms and adding the products together.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \left( \begin{matrix}
                -5 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
                4 \amp -5 \amp -7 \amp 1 \\
                1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -8 \\
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                4 \\ -1 \\ -1 \\ -1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow> 
              \amp = \left( \begin{matrix}
                (-5)(4) + (0)(-1) + (3)(-1) + (2)(-1) \\
                (4)(4) + (-5)(-1) + (-7)(-1) + (1)(-1) \\
                (1)(4) + (2)(-1) + (0)(-1) + (-8)(-1) 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              = \left( \begin{matrix}
                -25 \\ 27 \\ 10 
              \end{matrix} \right)
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate this matrix action.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              -1 \amp 6 \amp 0 \amp -4 \\
              0 \amp 3 \amp 3 \amp -12 \\
              -5 \amp -6 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\
