    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Take the matrix for rotation by <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m> radians
          in <m>\RR^2</m> and muliply it by itself to check that the
          result is the matrix for rotation by <m>\pi</m> radians.
          Multiply by the original matrix again and check that the
          result is now the matrix for rotation by
          <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The matrix for a quarter turn rotation is 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
          To compose transformations we multiply matrices. To compose
          this transformation with itself, I mutiply the matrix with
          itself. 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 
            \end{matrix} \right) = 
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
          The result of the matrix multiplication is indeed the
          rotation matrix for rotation by <m>\pi</m> radians. To see
          what happens after a third rotation by a quarter turn, I
          multiply this matrix by the original quarter turn matrix. 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 
            \end{matrix} \right) = 
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              0 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 0
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
          The result of the matrix multiplication is indeed the matrix
          of the rotation by <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m> radians. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-week6-proofs">
    <title>Proof Questions</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider two rotations in <m>\RR^2</m>, by angles
          <m>\theta</m> and <m>\phi</m>. Using the general form of a
          matrix for a rotation, prove that the composition of these
          two rotations is the rotation by the angle <m>(\theta +
          \phi)</m>. (You will need to use some trigonometric
          identities to prove this.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The general form of a rotation by <m>\theta</m> is 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              \cos \theta \amp - \sin \theta \\
              \sin \theta \amp \cos \theta
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>.
          I can make the same matrix for the angle <m>\phi</m>.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              \cos \phi \amp - \sin \phi \\
              \sin \phi \amp \cos \phi
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>.
          I compose these two matrices. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \left( \begin{matrix}
                \cos \theta \amp - \sin \theta \\
                \sin \theta \amp \cos \theta
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                \cos \phi \amp - \sin \phi \\
                \sin \phi \amp \cos \phi
              \end{matrix} \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \left( \begin{matrix}
                (\cos \theta) (\cos \phi) - (\sin \theta)(\sin \phi)
                \amp -(\cos \theta) (\sin \phi) - (\sin \theta)(\cos
                \phi) \\
                (\sin \theta) (\cos \phi) + (\cos \theta)(\sin \phi)
                \amp -(\sin \theta) (\sin \phi) + (\cos \theta)(\cos
                \phi) 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Now I need trig identities. Each of these four matrix
          entries is a sum identity. Replacing those according to
          identities drawn from the reference material,
          I get this matrix.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              \cos (\theta + \phi) \amp -\sin (\theta + \phi) \\
              \sin (\theta + \phi) \amp \cos (\theta + \phi)
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
          This is precisely the matrix form for rotation by the angle
          <m>(\theta + \phi)</m>. Therefore, I have proven that the
          matrix multiplication, and hence the composition, of two
          rotations produces the rotation by the sum of the two
          angles.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that any reflection in <m>\RR^2</m> composes with
          itself to produce the identity. (Use the general matrix for
          these reflections).
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The general form for a reflection over the line spanned by the
          <emph>unit</emph> vector <m>\left( \begin{matrix} a \\ b
          \end{matrix} \right)</m> is 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              a^2 - b^2 \amp 2ab \\ 
              2ab \amp b^2 - a^2 
            \end{matrix} \right)  
          </me>.
          Since the vector defining the line is a unit vector, I know
          <m>a^2 + b^2 =
          1</m>. This fact will be important to the proof. Now I take
          this matrix and multiply it by itself to do the composition
          of the reflection with itself. I'll have to do some algebra
          with the resulting terms in the new matrix. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \left( \begin{matrix}
                a^2 - b^2 \amp 2ab \\ 
                2ab \amp b^2 - a^2 
              \end{matrix} \right)  
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                a^2 - b^2 \amp 2ab \\ 
                2ab \amp b^2 - a^2 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \left( \begin{matrix}
                (a^2 - b^2)^2 + (2ab)(2ab) \amp
                (a^2-b^2)(2ab) + (2ab)(b^2-a^2) \\
                (2ab)(a^2-b^2) + (b^2-a^2)(2ab) \amp
                (2ab)(2ab) + (b^2-a^2)^2 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \left( \begin{matrix}
                a^4 - 2a^2b^2 + b^4 + 4a^2b^2 \amp
                (a^2-b^2)(2ab) - (a^2-b^2)(2ab) \\
                (2ab)(a^2-b^2) - (2ab)(a^2-b^2) \amp
                4a^2b^2 + b^4 - 2a^2b^2 + a^4 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \left( \begin{matrix}
                a^4 + 2a^2b^2 + b^4 \amp 0 \\
                0 \amp b^2 + 2a^2b^2 + a^2 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \left( \begin{matrix}
                (a^2+b^2)^2 \amp 0 \\
                0 \amp (a^2+b^2)^2 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \amp 0 \\
                0 \amp 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          In the last step, I use the important fact about the unit
          vector. I end up with the identity matrix, which is what I
          wanted, so the proof is finished. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
